# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: archaea
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] The genes coding for it are referred to as **16S rRNA genes** and are used in reconstructing phylogenies, due to the slow rates of evolution of this region of the gene.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Fox were two of the people who pioneered the use of 16S rRNA in phylogenetics in 1977.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Multiple sequences of the 16S rRNA gene can exist within a single bacterium.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] The descriptor *16S* refers to the size of these ribosomal subunits as reflected indirectly by the speed at which they sediment when samples are centrifuged.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] The 16S rRNA gene is used for phylogenetic studies as it is highly conserved between different species of bacteria and archaea.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Carl Woese pioneered this use of 16S rRNA in 1977.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] It is suggested that 16S rRNA gene can be used as a reliable molecular clock because 16S rRNA sequences from distantly related bacterial lineages are shown to have similar functionalities.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Some thermophilic archaea (e.g. order Thermoproteales) contain 16S rRNA gene introns that are located in highly conserved regions and can impact the annealing of "universal" primers.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Mitochondrial and chloroplastic rRNA are also amplified.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] The most common primer pair was devised by Weisburg *et al.* (1991) and is currently referred to as 27F and 1492R; however, for some applications shorter amplicons may be necessary, for example for 454 sequencing with titanium chemistry the primer pair 27F-534R covering V1 to V3.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] The two primers are almost identical, but 27F has an M instead of a C.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] AGAGTTTGATC**M**TGGCTCAG compared with 8F.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] In addition to highly conserved primer binding sites, 16S rRNA gene sequences contain hypervariable regions that can provide species-specific signature sequences useful for identification of bacteria.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] As a result, 16S rRNA gene sequencing has become prevalent in medical microbiology as a rapid and cheap alternative to phenotypic methods of bacterial identification.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Although it was originally used to identify bacteria, 16S sequencing was subsequently found to be capable of reclassifying bacteria into completely new species, or even genera.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] It has also been used to describe new species that have never been successfully cultured.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] With third-generation sequencing coming to many labs, simultaneous identification of thousands of 16S rRNA sequences is possible within hours, allowing metagenomic studies, for example of gut flora.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] In samples collected from patients with confirmed infections, 16S rRNA next-generation sequencing (NGS) demonstrated enhanced detection in 40% of cases compared to traditional culture methods; moreover, pre-sampling antibiotic consumption did not significantly affect the sensitivity of 16S NGS.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] The bacterial 16S gene contains nine hypervariable regions (V1–V9), ranging from about 30 to 100 base pairs long, that are involved in the secondary structure of the small ribosomal subunit.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] The degree of conservation varies widely between hypervariable regions, with more conserved regions correlating to higher-level taxonomy and less conserved regions to lower levels, such as genus and species.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] While the entire 16S sequence allows for comparison of all hypervariable regions, at approximately 1,500 base pairs long it can be prohibitively expensive for studies seeking to identify or characterize diverse bacterial communities.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] These studies commonly utilize the Illumina platform, which produces reads at rates 50-fold and 12,000-fold less expensive than 454 pyrosequencing and Sanger sequencing, respectively.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] While cheaper and allowing for deeper community coverage, Illumina sequencing only produces reads 75–250 base pairs long (up to 300 base pairs with Illumina MiSeq), and has no established protocol for reliably assembling the full gene in community samples.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Full hypervariable regions can be assembled from a single Illumina run, however, making them ideal targets for the platform.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] While 16S hypervariable regions can vary dramatically between bacteria, the 16S gene as a whole maintains greater length homogeneity than its eukaryotic counterpart (18S ribosomal RNA), which can make alignments easier.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Additionally, the 16S gene contains highly conserved sequences between hypervariable regions, enabling the design of universal primers that can reliably produce the same sections of the 16S sequence across different taxa.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Although no hypervariable region can accurately classify all bacteria from domain to species, some can reliably predict specific taxonomic levels.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Many community studies select semi-conserved hypervariable regions like the V4 for this reason, as it can provide resolution at the phylum level as accurately as the full 16S gene.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] While lesser-conserved regions struggle to classify new species when higher order taxonomy is unknown, they are often used to detect the presence of specific pathogens.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] In one study by Chakravorty et al. in 2007, the authors characterized the V1–V8 regions of a variety of pathogens in order to determine which hypervariable regions would be most useful to include for disease-specific and broad assays.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Amongst other findings, they noted that the V3 region was best at identifying the genus for all pathogens tested, and that V6 was the most accurate at differentiating species between all CDC-watched pathogens tested, including anthrax.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] While 16S hypervariable region analysis is a powerful tool for bacterial taxonomic studies, it struggles to differentiate between closely related species.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] In the families *Enterobacteriaceae*, *Clostridiaceae*, and *Peptostreptococcaceae*, species can share up to 99% sequence similarity across the full 16S gene.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] As a result, the V4 sequences can differ by only a few nucleotides, leaving reference databases unable to reliably classify these bacteria at lower taxonomic levels.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] By limiting 16S analysis to select hypervariable regions, these studies can fail to observe differences in closely related taxa and group them into single taxonomic units, therefore underestimating the total diversity of the sample.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Furthermore, bacterial genomes can house multiple 16S genes, with the V1, V2, and V6 regions containing the greatest intraspecies diversity.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] While not the most precise method of classifying bacterial species, analysis of the hypervariable regions remains one of the most useful tools available to bacterial community studies.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Under the assumption that evolution is driven by vertical transmission, 16S rRNA genes have long been believed to be species-specific, and infallible as genetic markers inferring phylogenetic relationships among prokaryotes.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] However, a growing number of observations suggest the occurrence of horizontal transfer of these genes.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] In addition to observations of natural occurrence, transferability of these genes is supported experimentally using a specialized *Escherichia coli* genetic system.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Using a null mutant of *E. coli* as host, growth of the mutant strain was shown to be complemented by foreign 16S rRNA genes that were phylogenetically distinct from *E. coli* at the phylum level.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Such functional compatibility was also seen in *Thermus thermophilus*.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Furthermore, in *T. thermophilus*, both complete and partial gene transfer was observed.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Partial transfer resulted in spontaneous generation of apparently random chimera between host and foreign bacterial genes.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Thus, 16S rRNA genes may have evolved through multiple mechanisms, including vertical inheritance and horizontal gene transfer; the frequency of the latter may be much higher than previously thought.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] The 16S rRNA gene is used as the standard for classification and identification of microbes, because it is present in most microbes and shows proper changes.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Type strains of 16S rRNA gene sequences for most bacteria and archaea are available on public databases, such as NCBI.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] However, the quality of the sequences found on these databases is often not validated.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Therefore, secondary databases that collect only 16S rRNA sequences are widely used.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] SILVA provides comprehensive, quality checked and regularly updated datasets of aligned small (16S/18S, SSU) and large subunit (23S/28S, LSU) ribosomal RNA (rRNA) sequences for all three domains of life as well as a suite of search, primer-design and alignment tools (Bacteria, Archaea and Eukarya).
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] GreenGenes is a quality controlled, comprehensive 16S rRNA gene reference database and taxonomy based on a *de novo* phylogeny that provides standard operational taxonomic unit sets.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] EzBioCloud database, formerly known as EzTaxon, consists of a complete hierarchical taxonomic system containing 62,988 bacteria and archaea species/phylotypes which includes 15,290 valid published names as of September 2018.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Based on the phylogenetic relationship such as maximum-likelihood and OrthoANI, all species/subspecies are represented by at least one 16S rRNA gene sequence.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] The EzBioCloud database is systematically curated and updated regularly which also includes novel candidate species.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Moreover, the website provides bioinformatics tools such as ANI calculator, ContEst16S and 16S rRNA DB for QIIME and Mothur pipeline.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] MIMt is a compact non-redundant 16S database for a rapid metagenomic samples identification.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] It is composed of 48,749 full 16S sequences belonging to 24,626 well classified bacteria and archaea species.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] All sequences were obtained from complete genomes deposited in NCBI and for each of the sequences full taxonomic hierarchy is provided.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] It contains no redundancy, so only one representative for each species was considered avoiding same sequences from different strains, isolates or pathovars resulting in a very fast tool for microorganisms identification, compatible with any classification software (QIIME, Mothur, DADA, etc).
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] The Ribosomal Database Project (RDP) was a curated database that offers ribosome data along with related programs and services.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] The offerings included phylogenetically ordered alignments of ribosomal RNA (rRNA) sequences, derived phylogenetic trees, rRNA secondary structure diagrams and various software packages for handling, analyzing and displaying alignments and trees.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] Due to its large size the RDP database is often used as the basis for bioinformatic tool development and creating manually curated databases.
[src:archaea/16s-ribosomal-rna] The RDP server was taken offline in 2023, but the software is still available for download.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:archaea/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The **abiogenic petroleum origin** hypothesis proposes that most of Earth's petroleum and natural gas deposits were formed inorganically, commonly known as **abiotic oil**.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Scientific evidence overwhelmingly supports a biogenic origin for most of the world's petroleum deposits.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Mainstream theories about the formation of hydrocarbons on Earth point to an origin from the decomposition of long-dead organisms, though the existence of hydrocarbons on extraterrestrial bodies like Saturn's moon Titan indicates that hydrocarbons are sometimes naturally produced by inorganic means.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] A historical overview of theories of the abiogenic origins of hydrocarbons has been published.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Thomas Gold's "deep gas hypothesis" proposes that some natural gas deposits were formed out of hydrocarbons deep in the Earth's mantle.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Earlier studies of mantle-derived rocks from many places have shown that hydrocarbons from the mantle region can be found widely around the globe.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, the concentration of such hydrocarbons is low.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] While there may be large deposits of abiotic hydrocarbons, globally significant amounts of abiotic hydrocarbons are deemed unlikely.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Some abiogenic hypotheses have proposed that oil and gas did not originate from fossil deposits, but have instead originated from deep carbon deposits, present since the formation of the Earth.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The abiogenic hypothesis regained some support in 2009 when researchers at the KTH Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm reported they believed they had proven that fossils from animals and plants are not necessary for crude oil and natural gas to be generated.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Abiogenic hypotheses were revived in the last half of the 20th century by Soviet scientists who had little influence outside the Soviet Union because most of their research was published in Russian.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The hypothesis was re-defined and made popular in the West by astronomer Thomas Gold, a prominent proponent of the abiogenic hypothesis, who developed his theories from 1979 to 1998 and published his research in English.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Abraham Gottlob Werner and the proponents of neptunism in the 18th century regarded basaltic sills as solidified oils or bitumen.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] While these notions proved unfounded, the basic idea of an association between petroleum and magmatism persisted.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Von Humboldt proposed an inorganic abiogenic hypothesis for petroleum formation after he observed petroleum springs in the Bay of Cumaux (Cumaná) on the northeast coast of Venezuela.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] He is quoted as saying, "the petroleum is the product of a distillation from great depth and issues from the primitive rocks beneath which the forces of all volcanic action lie".
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Other early prominent proponents of what would become the generalized abiogenic hypothesis included Dmitri Mendeleev and Berthelot.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] In 1951, the Soviet geologist Nikolai Alexandrovitch Kudryavtsev proposed the modern abiotic hypothesis of petroleum.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] On the basis of his analysis of the Athabasca Oil Sands in Alberta, Canada, he concluded that no "source rocks" could form the enormous volume of hydrocarbons, and therefore offered abiotic deep petroleum as the most plausible explanation.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] (Humic coals have since been proposed for the source rocks.) Others who continued Kudryavtsev's work included Petr N.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Following Thomas Gold's death in 2004, Jack Kenney of Gas Resources Corporation has recently come into prominence as a proponent of the theories, supported by studies by researchers at the Royal Institute of Technology (KTH) in Stockholm, Sweden.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Within the mantle, carbon may exist as hydrocarbons—chiefly methane—and as elemental carbon, carbon dioxide, and carbonates.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Abiogenic hypotheses generally reject the supposition that certain molecules found within petroleum, known as biomarkers, are indicative of the biological origin of petroleum.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] As of 2009, little research is directed towards establishing abiogenic petroleum or methane, although the Carnegie Institution for Science has reported that ethane and heavier hydrocarbons can be synthesized under conditions of the upper mantle.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Research mostly related to astrobiology and the deep microbial biosphere and serpentinite reactions, however, continues to provide insight into the contribution of abiogenic hydrocarbons into petroleum accumulations.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Thomas Gold's work was focused on hydrocarbon deposits of primordial origin.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Meteorites are believed to represent the major composition of material from which the Earth was formed.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Some meteorites, such as carbonaceous chondrites, contain carbonaceous material.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] If a large amount of this material is still within the Earth, it could have been leaking upward for billions of years.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The thermodynamic conditions within the mantle would allow many hydrocarbon molecules to be at equilibrium under high pressure and high temperature.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Although molecules in these conditions may disassociate, resulting fragments would be reformed due to the pressure.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] An average equilibrium of various molecules would exist depending upon conditions and the carbon-hydrogen ratio of the material.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Russian researchers concluded that hydrocarbon mixes would be created within the mantle.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Experiments under high temperatures and pressures produced many hydrocarbons—including n-alkanes through C10H22—from iron oxide, calcium carbonate, and water.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Because such materials are in the mantle and in subducted crust, there is no requirement that all hydrocarbons be produced from primordial deposits.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Hydrogen gas and water have been found more than 6,000 metres (20,000 ft) deep in the upper crust in the Siljan Ring boreholes and the Kola Superdeep Borehole.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Data from the western United States suggests that aquifers from near the surface may extend to depths of 10,000 metres (33,000 ft) to 20,000 metres (66,000 ft).
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Hydrogen gas can be created by water reacting with silicates, quartz, and feldspar at temperatures in the range of 25 °C (77 °F) to 270 °C (518 °F).
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] These minerals are common in crustal rocks such as granite.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Hydrogen may react with dissolved carbon compounds in water to form methane and higher carbon compounds.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The above reaction operates best at low pressures.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] At pressures greater than 5 gigapascals (49,000 atm), almost no hydrogen is formed.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Thomas Gold reported that hydrocarbons were found in the Siljan Ring borehole and in general increased with depth, although the venture was not a commercial success.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, several geologists analysed the results and said that no hydrocarbon was found.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] In 1967, the Soviet scientist Emmanuil B.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Chekaliuk proposed that petroleum could be formed at high temperatures and pressures from inorganic carbon in the form of carbon dioxide, hydrogen or methane.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] This mechanism is supported by several lines of evidence which are accepted by modern scientific literature.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] This involves synthesis of oil within the crust via catalysis by chemically reductive rocks.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] A proposed mechanism for the formation of inorganic hydrocarbons is via natural analogs of the Fischer–Tropsch process known as the *serpentinite mechanism* or the serpentinite process.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Serpentinites are ideal rocks to host this process as they are formed from peridotites and dunites, rocks which contain greater than 80% olivine and usually a percentage of Fe-Ti spinel minerals.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Most olivines also contain high nickel concentrations (up to several percent) and may also contain chromite or chromium as a contaminant in olivine, providing the needed transition metals.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, serpentinite synthesis and spinel cracking reactions require hydrothermal alteration of pristine peridotite-dunite, which is a finite process intrinsically related to metamorphism, and further, requires significant addition of water.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Serpentinite is unstable at mantle temperatures and is readily dehydrated to granulite, amphibolite, talc–schist and even eclogite.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] This suggests that methanogenesis in the presence of serpentinites is restricted in space and time to mid-ocean ridges and upper levels of subduction zones.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, water has been found as deep as 12,000 metres (39,000 ft), so water-based reactions are dependent upon the local conditions.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Oil being created by this process in intracratonic regions is limited by the materials and temperature.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] A chemical basis for the abiotic petroleum process is the serpentinization of peridotite, beginning with methanogenesis via hydrolysis of olivine into serpentine in the presence of carbon dioxide.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Olivine, composed of Forsterite and Fayalite metamorphoses into serpentine, magnetite and silica by the following reactions, with silica from fayalite decomposition (reaction 1a) feeding into the forsterite reaction (1b).
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] When this reaction occurs in the presence of dissolved carbon dioxide (carbonic acid) at temperatures above 500 °C (932 °F) Reaction 2a takes place.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The upgrading of methane to higher n-alkane hydrocarbons is via dehydrogenation of methane in the presence of catalyst transition metals (e.g.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Magnetite, chromite and ilmenite are Fe-spinel group minerals found in many rocks but rarely as a major component in non-ultramafic rocks.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] In these rocks, high concentrations of magmatic magnetite, chromite and ilmenite provide a reduced matrix which may allow abiotic cracking of methane to higher hydrocarbons during hydrothermal events.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Chemically reduced rocks are required to drive this reaction and high temperatures are required to allow methane to be polymerized to ethane.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Note that reaction 1a, above, also creates magnetite.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Reaction 3 results in n-alkane hydrocarbons, including linear saturated hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes, ketones, aromatics, and cyclic compounds.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Note that CaO (lime) is not a mineral species found within natural rocks.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Whilst this reaction is possible, it is not plausible.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The "deep biotic petroleum hypothesis", similar to the abiogenic petroleum origin hypothesis, holds that not all petroleum deposits within the Earth's rocks can be explained purely according to the orthodox view of petroleum geology.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Thomas Gold used the term "the deep hot biosphere" to describe the microbes which live underground.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] This hypothesis is different from biogenic oil in that the role of deep-dwelling microbes is a biological source for oil which is not of a sedimentary origin and is not sourced from surface carbon.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Deep microbial life is only a contaminant of primordial hydrocarbons.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Parts of microbes yield molecules as biomarkers.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Deep biotic oil is considered to be formed as a byproduct of the life cycle of deep microbes.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Shallow biotic oil is considered to be formed as a byproduct of the life cycles of shallow microbes.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Thomas Gold, in a 1999 book, cited the discovery of thermophile bacteria in the Earth's crust as new support for the postulate that these bacteria could explain the existence of certain biomarkers in extracted petroleum.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] A rebuttal of biogenic origins based on biomarkers has been offered by Kenney, et al.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Methane is ubiquitous in crustal fluid and gas.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Research continues to attempt to characterise crustal sources of methane as biogenic or abiogenic using carbon isotope fractionation of observed gases (Lollar & Sherwood 2006).
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] One argument for abiogenic oil cites the high carbon depletion of methane as stemming from the observed carbon isotope depletion with depth in the crust.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, diamonds, which are definitively of mantle origin, are not as depleted as methane, which implies that methane carbon isotope fractionation is not controlled by mantle values.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Commercially extractable concentrations of helium (greater than 0.3%) are present in natural gas from the Panhandle-Hugoton fields in the US, as well as from some Algerian and Russian gas fields.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Helium trapped within most petroleum occurrences, such as the occurrence in Texas, is of a distinctly crustal character with an *Ra* ratio of less than 0.0001 that of the atmosphere.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Certain chemicals found in naturally occurring petroleum contain chemical and structural similarities to compounds found within many living organisms.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] These include terpenoids, terpenes, pristane, phytane, cholestane, chlorins and porphyrins, which are large, chelating molecules in the same family as heme and chlorophyll.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Materials which suggest certain biological processes include tetracyclic diterpane and oleanane.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The presence of these chemicals in crude oil is a result of the inclusion of biological material in the oil; these chemicals are released by kerogen during the production of hydrocarbon oils, as these are chemicals highly resistant to degradation and plausible chemical paths have been studied.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Abiotic defenders state that biomarkers get into oil during its way up as it gets in touch with ancient fossils.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However a more plausible explanation is that biomarkers are traces of biological molecules from bacteria (archaea) that feed on primordial hydrocarbons and die in that environment.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] For example, hopanoids are just parts of the bacterial cell wall present in oil as a contaminant.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Nickel (Ni), vanadium (V), lead (Pb), arsenic (As), cadmium (Cd), mercury (Hg) and others metals frequently occur in oils.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Some heavy crude oils, such as Venezuelan heavy crude have up to 45% vanadium pentoxide content in their ash, high enough that it is a commercial source for vanadium.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Abiotic supporters argue that these metals are common in Earth's mantle, but relatively high contents of nickel, vanadium, lead and arsenic can be usually found in almost all marine sediments.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Analysis of 22 trace elements in oils correlate significantly better with chondrite, serpentinized fertile mantle peridotite, and the primitive mantle than with oceanic or continental crust, and shows no correlation with seawater.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Sir Robert Robinson studied the chemical makeup of natural petroleum oils in great detail, and concluded that they were mostly far too hydrogen-rich to be a likely product of the decay of plant debris, assuming a dual origin for Earth hydrocarbons.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, several processes which generate hydrogen could supply kerogen hydrogenation which is compatible with the conventional explanation.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Olefins, the unsaturated hydrocarbons, would have been expected to predominate by far in any material that was derived in that way.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] This hypothesis was later demonstrated to have been a misunderstanding by Robinson, related to the fact that only short duration experiments were available to him.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Olefins are thermally very unstable (which is why natural petroleum normally does not contain such compounds) and in laboratory experiments that last more than a few hours, the olefins are no longer present.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The presence of low-oxygen and hydroxyl-poor hydrocarbons in natural living media is supported by the presence of natural waxes (n=30+), oils (n=20+) and lipids in both plant matter and animal matter, for instance fats in phytoplankton, zooplankton and so on.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] These oils and waxes, however, occur in quantities too small to significantly affect the overall hydrogen/carbon ratio of biological materials.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, after the discovery of highly aliphatic biopolymers in algae, and that oil generating kerogen essentially represents concentrates of such materials, no theoretical problem exists anymore.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Also, the millions of source rock samples that have been analyzed for petroleum yield by the petroleum industry have confirmed the large quantities of petroleum found in sedimentary basins.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Occurrences of abiotic petroleum in commercial amounts in the oil wells in offshore Vietnam are sometimes cited, as well as in the Eugene Island block 330 oil field, and the Dnieper-Donets Basin.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, the origins of all these wells can also be explained with the biotic theory.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Modern geologists think that commercially profitable deposits of abiotic petroleum *could* be found, but no current deposit has convincing evidence that it originated from abiotic sources.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The Soviet school of thought saw evidence of their hypothesis in the fact that some oil reservoirs exist in non-sedimentary rocks such as granite, metamorphic or porous volcanic rocks.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, opponents noted that non-sedimentary rocks served as reservoirs for biologically originated oil expelled from nearby sedimentary source rock through common migration or re-migration mechanisms.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The Lost City hydrothermal field was determined to have abiogenic hydrocarbon production.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Proskurowski et al. wrote, "Radiocarbon evidence rules out seawater bicarbonate as the carbon source for FTT reactions, suggesting that a mantle-derived inorganic carbon source is leached from the host rocks.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, some geochemists concluded by geochemical analysis that the oil in the seeps came from the organic-rich Ordovician Tretaspis shale, where it was heated by the meteorite impact.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] In 1986–1990, the Gravberg-1 borehole was drilled through the deepest rock in the Siljan Ring in which proponents had hoped to find hydrocarbon reservoirs.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] It stopped at the depth of 6,800 metres (22,300 ft) due to drilling problems, after private investors spent $40 million.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] This well also sampled over 13,000 feet (4,000 m) of methane-bearing inclusions.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] In 1991–1992, a second borehole, Stenberg-1, was drilled a few miles away to a depth of 6,500 metres (21,300 ft), finding similar results.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Direct observation of bacterial mats and fracture-fill carbonate and humin of bacterial origin in deep boreholes in Australia are also taken as evidence for the abiogenic origin of petroleum.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Panhandle-Hugoton field (Anadarko Basin) in the south-central United States is the most important gas field with commercial helium content.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Some abiogenic proponents interpret this as evidence that both the helium and the natural gas came from the mantle.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The Bạch Hổ oil field in Vietnam has been proposed as an example of abiogenic oil because it is 4,000 m of fractured basement granite, at a depth of 5,000 m.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] However, others argue that it contains biogenic oil which leaked into the basement horst from conventional source rocks within the Cửu Long basin.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] A major component of mantle-derived carbon is indicated in commercial gas reservoirs in the Pannonian and Vienna basins of Hungary and Austria.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Natural gas pools interpreted as being mantle-derived are the Shengli Field and Songliao Basin, northeastern China.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The Chimaera gas seep, near Çıralı, Antalya (southwest Turkey), has been continuously active for millennia and it is known to be the source of the first Olympic fire in the Hellenistic period.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Local geology of Chimaera flames, at exact position of flames, reveals contact between serpentinized ophiolite and carbonate rocks.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Fischer–Tropsch process can be suitable reaction to form hydrocarbon gases.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] What unites both theories of oil origin is the low success rate in predicting the locations of giant oil/gas fields: according to the statistics discovering a giant demands drilling 500+ exploration wells.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] A team of American-Russian scientists (mathematicians, geologists, geophysicists, and computer scientists) developed an Artificial Intelligence software and the appropriate technology for geological applications, and used it for predicting places of giant oil/gas deposits.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] In 1986, the team published a prognostic map for discovering giant oil and gas fields at the Andes in South America based on abiogenic petroleum origin theory.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Yury Pikovsky (Moscow State University) assumes that petroleum moves from the mantle to the surface through permeable channels created at the intersection of deep faults.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The technology uses 1) maps of morphostructural zoning, which outlines the morphostructural nodes (intersections of faults), and 2) pattern recognition program that identify nodes containing giant oil/gas fields.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] It was forecast that eleven nodes, which had not been developed at that time, contain giant oil or gas fields.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] These 11 sites covered only 8% of the total area of all the Andes basins.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] 30 years later (in 2018) was published the result of comparing the prognosis and the reality.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Since the publication of the prognostic map in 1986, six giant oil/gas fields were discovered in the Andes region: Caño Limón oilfield, Cusiana, Capiagua, Colombia, and Volcanera (Llanos basin, Colombia), Camisea (Ukayali basin, Peru), and Incahuasi (Chaco basin, Bolivia).
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] All discoveries were made in places shown on the 1986 prognostic map as promising areas.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] During the 1960s, Donald Hings was issued numerous patents for developing practical methods for locating likely locations of the deep morphological nodes most likely to indicate the presence of abiogenic hydrocarbons.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] His methods and technologies are used to this day by geophysicists to locate deep hydrocarbon deposits.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] The presence of methane on Saturn's moon Titan and in the atmospheres of Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and Neptune is cited as evidence of the formation of hydrocarbons without biological intermediate forms, for example by Thomas Gold.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] (Terrestrial natural gas is composed primarily of methane).
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Some comets contain massive amounts of organic compounds, the equivalent of cubic kilometers of such mixed with other material; for instance, corresponding hydrocarbons were detected during a probe flyby through the tail of Halley's Comet in 1986.
[src:archaea/abiogenic-petroleum-origin] Drill samples from the surface of Mars taken in 2015 by the Curiosity Rover's Mars Science Laboratory revealed the presence of benzene and propane in 3 billion-year-old rock samples taken from Gale Crater.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:archaea/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea were initially classified as bacteria, receiving the name archaebacteria (/ˌɑːrkibækˈtɪəriə/, in the Archaebacteria kingdom), but this term has fallen out of use.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaeal cells have unique properties distinguishing them from Bacteria and Eukaryota, including: cell membranes made of ether-linked lipids; metabolisms such as methanogenesis; and a unique motility structure known as an archaellum.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea are further divided into multiple recognized phyla.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Classification is difficult because most have not been isolated in a laboratory and have been identified only by their gene sequences in environmental samples.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] They have not been observed to produce endospores.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea are often similar to bacteria in size and shape, although a few have very different shapes, such as the flat, square cells of *Haloquadratum walsbyi*.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Despite this, archaea possess genes and several metabolic pathways that are more closely related to those of eukaryotes, notably for the enzymes involved in transcription and translation.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Other aspects of archaeal biochemistry are unique, such as their reliance on ether lipids in their cell membranes, including archaeols.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea use more diverse energy sources than eukaryotes, ranging from organic compounds such as sugars, to ammonia, metal ions or even hydrogen gas.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The salt-tolerant Halobacteria use sunlight as an energy source, and other species of archaea fix carbon (autotrophy), but unlike cyanobacteria, no known species of archaea does both.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea reproduce asexually by binary fission, fragmentation, or budding; unlike bacteria, no known species of Archaea form endospores.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The first observed archaea were extremophiles, living in extreme environments such as hot springs and salt lakes with no other organisms.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Improved molecular detection tools led to the discovery of archaea in almost every habitat, including soil, oceans, and marshlands.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea are particularly numerous in the oceans, and the archaea in plankton may be one of the most abundant groups of organisms on the planet.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea are a major part of Earth's life.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] They are part of the microbiota of all organisms.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In the human microbiome, they are important in the gut, mouth, and on the skin.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Their morphological, metabolic, and geographical diversity permits them to play multiple ecological roles: carbon fixation; nitrogen cycling; organic compound turnover; and maintaining microbial symbiotic and syntrophic communities, for example.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] As of 2024, only one species of archaea has been found to be parasitic; many are mutualists or commensals, such as the methanogens (methane-producers) that inhabit the gastrointestinal tract in humans and ruminants, where their vast numbers facilitate digestion.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Methanogens are used in biogas production and sewage treatment, while biotechnology exploits enzymes from extremophile archaea that can endure high temperatures and organic solvents.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] For much of the 20th century, prokaryotes were regarded as a single group of organisms and classified based on their biochemistry, morphology and metabolism.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Microbiologists tried to classify microorganisms based on the structures of their cell walls, their shapes, and the substances they consume.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In 1965, Emile Zuckerkandl and Linus Pauling instead proposed using the sequences of the genes in different prokaryotes to work out how they are related to each other.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This phylogenetic approach is the main method used today.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The first archaea to be isolated and grown in pure culture were methane-producing species in the genera Methanobacterium and Methanococcus in the 1930s and 1940s, although at the time, they were classified as bacteria.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea were first classified separately from bacteria in 1977 by Carl Woese and George E.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Fox, based on their ribosomal RNA (rRNA) genes.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] (At that time only the methanogens were known).
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] They called these groups the *Urkingdoms* of Archaebacteria and Eubacteria, though other researchers treated them as kingdoms or subkingdoms.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Woese and Fox gave the first evidence for Archaebacteria as a separate "line of descent": 1. lack of peptidoglycan in their cell walls, 2. two unusual coenzymes, 3. results of 16S ribosomal RNA gene sequencing.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] To emphasize this difference, Woese, Otto Kandler and Mark Wheelis later proposed reclassifying organisms into three then thought to be natural domains known as the three-domain system: the Eukarya, the Bacteria and the Archaea, in what is now known as the Woesian Revolution.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Extreme halophilic and hyperthermophilic microbes were also included in Archaea.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] For a long time, archaea were seen as extremophiles that exist only in extreme habitats such as hot springs and salt lakes, but by the end of the 20th century, archaea had been identified in non-extreme environments as well.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Today, they are known to be a large and diverse group of organisms abundantly distributed throughout nature.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This new appreciation of the importance and ubiquity of archaea came from using polymerase chain reaction (PCR) to detect prokaryotes from environmental samples (such as water or soil) by multiplying their ribosomal genes.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This allows the detection and identification of organisms that have not been cultured in the laboratory.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The classification of archaea, and of prokaryotes in general, is a rapidly moving and contentious field.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Current classification systems aim to organize archaea into groups of organisms that share structural features and common ancestors.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These classifications rely heavily on the use of the sequence of ribosomal RNA genes to reveal relationships among organisms (molecular phylogenetics).
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Most of the culturable and well-investigated species of archaea are members of two main kingdoms, the Methanobacteriati and the Thermoproteati (formerly TACK).
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Other groups have been tentatively created, such as the peculiar species *Nanoarchaeum equitans* – discovered in 2003 and assigned its own phylum, the Nanoarchaeota (reassigned to Nanobdellota in 2023).
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] A new phylum "Korarchaeota" (now Thermoproteota) has also been proposed, containing a small group of unusual thermophilic species sharing features of both the main phyla.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Other detected species of archaea are only distantly related to any of these groups, such as the Archaeal Richmond Mine acidophilic nanoorganisms (ARMAN, comprising Micrarchaeota and Parvarchaeota), which were discovered in 2006 and are some of the smallest organisms known.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] A superphylum – "TACK" (now kingdom Thermoproteati) – which includes the Thaumarchaeota (now Nitrososphaerota), "Augarchaeota", Crenarchaeota (now Thermoproteota), and "Korarchaeota" (now Thermoproteota) was proposed in 2011 to be related to the origin of eukaryotes.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In 2017, the newly discovered and newly named "Asgard" (now kingdom Promethearchaeati) superphylum was proposed to be more closely related to the original eukaryote and a sister group to Thermoproteati / "TACK".
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In 2013, the superphylum "DPANN" (now kingdom Nanobdellati) was proposed to group "Nanoarchaeota", "Nanohaloarchaeota", Archaeal Richmond Mine acidophilic nanoorganisms (ARMAN, comprising "Micrarchaeota" and "Parvarchaeota"), and other similar archaea.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This archaeal superphylum encompasses at least 10 different lineages and includes organisms with extremely small cell and genome sizes and limited metabolic capabilities.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Therefore, Nanobdellati/"DPANN" may include members obligately dependent on symbiotic interactions, and may even include novel parasites.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] However, other phylogenetic analyses found that Nanobdellati/"DPANN" does not form a monophyletic group, and that the apparent grouping is caused by long branch attraction (LBA), suggesting that all these lineages belong to Methanobacteriati.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The classification of archaea into species is also controversial.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Ernst Mayr's species definition – a reproductively isolated group of interbreeding organisms - does not apply, as archaea reproduce only asexually.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea show high levels of horizontal gene transfer between lineages.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Some researchers suggest that individuals can be grouped into species-like populations given highly similar genomes and infrequent gene transfer to/from cells with less-related genomes, as in the genus *Ferroplasma*.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] On the other hand, studies in *Halorubrum* found significant genetic transfer to/from less-related populations, limiting the criterion's applicability.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Some researchers question whether such species designations have practical meaning.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Current knowledge on genetic diversity in archaeans is fragmentary, so the total number of species cannot be estimated with any accuracy.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Estimates of the number of phyla range from 18 to 23, of which only 8 have representatives that have been cultured and studied directly.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Many of these hypothesized groups are known from a single rRNA sequence, so the level of diversity remains obscure.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This situation is also seen in the Bacteria; many uncultured microbes present similar issues with characterization.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The age of the Earth is about 4.54 billion years.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Scientific evidence suggests that life began on Earth at least 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The earliest evidence for life on Earth is graphite found to be biogenic in 3.7-billion-year-old metasedimentary rocks discovered in Western Greenland and microbial mat fossils found in 3.48-billion-year-old sandstone discovered in Western Australia.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In 2015, possible remains of biotic matter were found in 4.1-billion-year-old rocks in Western Australia.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Although probable prokaryotic cell fossils date to almost 3.5 billion years ago, most prokaryotes do not have distinctive morphologies, and fossil shapes cannot be used to identify them as archaea.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Instead, chemical fossils of unique lipids are more informative because such compounds do not occur in other organisms.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Some publications suggest that archaeal or eukaryotic lipid remains are present in shales dating from 2.7 billion years ago, though such data have since been questioned.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These lipids have also been detected in even older rocks from west Greenland.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The oldest such traces come from the Isua district, which includes Earth's oldest known sediments, formed 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The archaeal lineage may be the most ancient that exists on Earth.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Woese argued that the bacteria, archaea, and eukaryotes represent separate lines of descent that diverged early on from an ancestral colony of organisms.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] One possibility is that this occurred before the evolution of cells, when the lack of a typical cell membrane allowed unrestricted lateral gene transfer, and that the common ancestors of the three domains arose by fixation of specific subsets of genes.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] It is possible that the last common ancestor of bacteria and archaea was a thermophile, which raises the possibility that lower temperatures are "extreme environments" for archaea, and organisms that live in cooler environments appeared only later.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Since archaea and bacteria are no more related to each other than they are to eukaryotes, the term *prokaryote* may suggest a false similarity between them.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] However, structural and functional similarities between lineages often occur because of shared ancestral traits or evolutionary convergence.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These similarities are known as a *grade*, and prokaryotes are best thought of as a grade of life, characterized by such features as an absence of membrane-bound organelles.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The following table compares some major characteristics of the three domains, to illustrate their similarities and differences.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea were split off as a third domain because of the large differences in their ribosomal RNA structure.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The particular molecule 16S rRNA is key to the production of proteins in all organisms.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Because this function is so central to life, organisms with mutations in their 16S rRNA are unlikely to survive, leading to great (but not absolute) stability in the structure of this polynucleotide over generations.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] 16S rRNA is large enough to show organism-specific variations, but still small enough to be compared quickly.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In 1977, Carl Woese, a microbiologist studying the genetic sequences of organisms, developed a new comparison method that involved splitting the RNA into fragments that could be sorted and compared with other fragments from other organisms.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The more similar the patterns between species, the more closely they are related.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Woese used his new rRNA comparison method to categorize and contrast different organisms.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] He compared a variety of species and happened upon a group of methanogens with rRNA vastly different from any known prokaryotes or eukaryotes.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These methanogens were much more similar to each other than to other organisms, leading Woese to propose the new domain of Archaea.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] His experiments showed that the archaea were genetically more similar to eukaryotes than prokaryotes, even though they were more similar to prokaryotes in structure.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This led to the conclusion that Archaea and Eukarya shared a common ancestor more recent than Eukarya and Bacteria.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The development of the nucleus occurred after the split between Bacteria and this common ancestor.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] One property unique to archaea is the abundant use of ether-linked lipids in their cell membranes.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Ether linkages are more chemically stable than the ester linkages found in bacteria and eukarya, which may be a contributing factor to the ability of many archaea to survive in extreme environments that place heavy stress on cell membranes, such as extreme heat and salinity.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Comparative analysis of archaeal genomes has also identified several molecular conserved signature indels and signature proteins uniquely present in either all archaea or different main groups within archaea.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Another unique feature of archaea, found in no other organisms, is methanogenesis (the metabolic production of methane).
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Methanogenic archaea play a pivotal role in ecosystems with organisms that derive energy from oxidation of methane, many of which are bacteria, as they are often a major source of methane in such environments and can play a role as primary producers.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Methanogens also play a critical role in the carbon cycle, breaking down organic carbon into methane, which is also a major greenhouse gas.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This difference in the biochemical structure of Bacteria and Archaea has been explained by researchers through evolutionary processes.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] It is theorized that both domains originated at deep sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] At least twice, microbes evolved lipid biosynthesis and cell wall biochemistry.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] It has been suggested that the last universal common ancestor was a non-free-living organism.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] It may have had a permeable membrane composed of bacterial simple chain amphiphiles (fatty acids), including archaeal simple chain amphiphiles (isoprenoids).
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These stabilize fatty acid membranes in seawater; this property may have driven the divergence of bacterial and archaeal membranes, "with the later biosynthesis of phospholipids giving rise to the unique G1P and G3P headgroups of archaea and bacteria respectively.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] If so, the properties conferred by membrane isoprenoids place the lipid divide as early as the origin of life".
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The relationships among the three domains are of central importance for understanding the origin of life.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Most of the metabolic pathways, which are the object of the majority of an organism's genes, are common between Archaea and Bacteria, while most genes involved in gene expression are common between Archaea and Eukarya.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Within prokaryotes, archaeal cell structure is most similar to that of Gram-positive bacteria, largely because both have a single lipid bilayer and usually contain a thick sacculus (exoskeleton) of varying chemical composition.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In some phylogenetic trees based upon different gene / protein sequences of prokaryotic homologs, the archaeal homologs are more closely related to those of gram-positive bacteria.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea and gram-positive bacteria also share conserved indels in a number of important proteins, such as Hsp70 and glutamine synthetase I; but the phylogeny of these genes was interpreted to reveal inter-domain gene transfer, and might not reflect the organismal relationship(s).
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] It has been proposed that the archaea evolved from Gram-positive bacteria in response to antibiotic selection pressure.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This is suggested by the observation that archaea are resistant to a wide variety of antibiotics that are produced primarily by Gram-positive bacteria, and that these antibiotics act primarily on the genes that distinguish archaea from bacteria.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The proposal is that the selective pressure towards resistance generated by the gram-positive antibiotics was eventually sufficient to cause extensive changes in many of the antibiotics' target genes, and that these strains represented the common ancestors of present-day Archaea.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This proposal is also supported by other work investigating protein structural relationships and studies that suggest that gram-positive bacteria may constitute the earliest branching lineages within the prokaryotes.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The evolutionary relationship between archaea and eukaryotes remains unclear.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Aside from the similarities in cell structure and function that are discussed below, many genetic trees group the two.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The standard hypothesis states that the ancestor of the eukaryotes diverged early from the Archaea, and that eukaryotes arose through symbiogenesis, the fusion of an archaean and a eubacterium, which formed the mitochondria; this hypothesis explains the genetic similarities between the groups.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The eocyte hypothesis instead posits that Eukaryota emerged relatively late from the Archaea.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] A lineage of archaea discovered in 2015, *Lokiarchaeum* (of the proposed new phylum "Lokiarchaeota"), named for a hydrothermal vent called Loki's Castle in the Arctic Ocean, was found to be the most closely related to eukaryotes known at that time.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] It has been called a transitional organism between prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Several sister phyla of "Lokiarchaeota" have since been found ("Thorarchaeota", "Odinarchaeota", "Heimdallarchaeota"), all together comprising a newly proposed supergroup "Asgard".
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea range from 0.1 micrometers (μm) to over 15 μm in diameter, and commonly occur as spheres, rods, spirals or plates.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Morphologies in the Thermoproteota also include irregularly shaped lobed cells in *Sulfolobus*, needle-like filaments that are less than half a micrometer in diameter in *Thermofilum*, and almost perfectly rectangular rods in *Thermoproteus* and *Pyrobaculum*.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea in the genus *Haloquadratum* such as *Haloquadratum walsbyi* are flat, square specimens that live in hypersaline pools.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These unusual shapes are probably maintained by both their cell walls and a prokaryotic cytoskeleton.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Proteins related to the cytoskeleton components of other organisms exist in archaea, and filaments form within their cells, but in contrast with other organisms, these cellular structures are poorly understood.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In *Thermoplasma* and *Ferroplasma* the lack of a cell wall means that the cells have irregular shapes, and can resemble amoebae.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Some species form aggregates or filaments of cells up to 200 μm long.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These organisms can be prominent in biofilms.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Notably, aggregates of *Thermococcus coalescens* cells fuse together in culture, forming single giant cells.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea in the genus *Pyrodictium* produce an elaborate multicell colony involving arrays of long, thin hollow tubes called *cannulae* that stick out from the cells' surfaces and connect them into a dense bush-like agglomeration.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The function of these cannulae is not settled, but they may allow communication or nutrient exchange with neighbors.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Multi-species colonies exist, such as the "string-of-pearls" community that was discovered in 2001 in a German swamp.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Round whitish colonies of a novel Methanobacteriati species are spaced along thin filaments that can range up to 15 centimetres (5.9 in) long; these filaments are made of a particular bacteria species.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea and bacteria have generally similar cell structure, but cell composition and organization set the archaea apart.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Like bacteria, archaea lack interior membranes and organelles.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Like bacteria, the cell membranes of archaea are usually bounded by a cell wall and they swim using one or more flagella.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Structurally, archaea are most similar to gram-positive bacteria.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Most have a single plasma membrane and cell wall, and lack a periplasmic space; the exception to this general rule is *Ignicoccus*, which possess a particularly large periplasm that contains membrane-bound vesicles and is enclosed by an outer membrane.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Most archaea (but not *Thermoplasma* and *Ferroplasma*) possess a cell wall.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In most archaea, the wall is assembled from surface-layer proteins, which form an S-layer.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] An S-layer is a rigid array of protein molecules that cover the outside of the cell (like chain mail).
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This layer provides both chemical and physical protection, and can prevent macromolecules from contacting the cell membrane.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Unlike bacteria, archaea lack peptidoglycan in their cell walls.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaeal flagella are known as archaella, that operate like bacterial flagella – their long stalks are driven by rotatory motors at the base.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These motors are powered by a proton gradient across the membrane, but archaella are notably different in composition and development.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The two types of flagella evolved from different ancestors.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The bacterial flagellum shares a common ancestor with the type III secretion system, while archaeal flagella appear to have evolved from bacterial type IV pili.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In contrast with the bacterial flagellum, which is hollow and assembled by subunits moving up the central pore to the tip of the flagella, archaeal flagella are synthesized by adding subunits at the base.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaeal membranes are made of different molecules from those in bacterial and eukaryotic membranes.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In all organisms, cell membranes are made of molecules known as phospholipids.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These molecules possess both a polar part that dissolves in water (the phosphate "head"), and a "greasy" non-polar part that does not (the lipid tail).
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These dissimilar parts are connected by a glycerol moiety.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In water, phospholipids cluster, with the heads facing the water and the tails facing away from it.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The major structure in cell membranes is a double layer of these phospholipids, which is called a lipid bilayer.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea exhibit a great variety of chemical reactions in their metabolism and use many sources of energy.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These reactions are classified into nutritional groups, depending on energy and carbon sources.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Some archaea obtain energy from inorganic compounds such as sulfur or ammonia (they are chemotrophs).
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These include nitrifiers, methanogens and anaerobic methane oxidisers.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In these reactions, one compound passes electrons to another (in a redox reaction), releasing energy to fuel the cell's activities.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] One compound acts as an electron donor and one as an electron acceptor.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The energy released is used to generate adenosine triphosphate (ATP) through chemiosmosis, the same basic process that happens in the mitochondrion of eukaryotic cells.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Other groups of archaea use sunlight as a source of energy (they are phototrophs), but oxygen–generating photosynthesis does not occur in any of these organisms.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Many basic metabolic pathways are shared among all forms of life; for example, archaea use a modified form of glycolysis (the Entner–Doudoroff pathway) and either a complete or partial citric acid cycle.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These similarities to other organisms probably reflect both early origins in the history of life and their high level of efficiency.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Some Methanobacteriati are methanogens (archaea that produce methane as a result of metabolism) living in anaerobic environments, such as swamps.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This form of metabolism evolved early, and it is even possible that the first free-living organism was a methanogen.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] A common reaction involves the use of carbon dioxide as an electron acceptor to oxidize hydrogen.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Methanogenesis involves a range of coenzymes that are unique to these archaea, such as coenzyme M and methanofuran.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Other organic compounds such as alcohols, acetic acid or formic acid are used as alternative electron acceptors by methanogens.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These reactions are common in gut-dwelling archaea.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Acetic acid is also broken down into methane and carbon dioxide directly, by *acetotrophic* archaea.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These acetotrophs are archaea in the order Methanosarcinales, and are a major part of the communities of microorganisms that produce biogas.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Other archaea use CO 2 in the atmosphere as a source of carbon, in a process called carbon fixation (they are autotrophs).
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This process involves either a highly modified form of the Calvin cycle or another metabolic pathway called the 3-hydroxypropionate / 4-hydroxybutyrate cycle.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The Thermoproteota also use the reverse Krebs cycle while the Methanobacteriati also use the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Carbon fixation is powered by inorganic energy sources.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] No known archaea carry out photosynthesis.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaeal energy sources are extremely diverse, and range from the oxidation of ammonia by the Nitrosopumilales to the oxidation of hydrogen sulfide or elemental sulfur by species of *Sulfolobus*, using either oxygen or metal ions as electron acceptors.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Phototrophic archaea use light to produce chemical energy in the form of ATP.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In the Halobacteria, light-activated ion pumps like bacteriorhodopsin and halorhodopsin generate ion gradients by pumping ions out of and into the cell across the plasma membrane.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The energy stored in these electrochemical gradients is then converted into ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This process is a form of photophosphorylation.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The ability of these light-driven pumps to move ions across membranes depends on light-driven changes in the structure of a retinol cofactor buried in the center of the protein.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea usually have a single circular chromosome, but many euryarchaea have been shown to bear multiple copies of this chromosome.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The largest known archaeal genome as of 2002 was 5,751,492 base pairs in *Methanosarcina acetivorans*.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The tiny 490,885 base-pair genome of *Nanoarchaeum equitans* is one-tenth of this size and the smallest archaeal genome known; it is estimated to contain only 537 protein-encoding genes.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Smaller independent pieces of DNA, called *plasmids*, are also found in archaea.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Plasmids may be transferred between cells by physical contact, in a process that may be similar to bacterial conjugation.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea are genetically distinct from bacteria and eukaryotes, with up to 15% of the proteins encoded by any one archaeal genome being unique to the domain, although most of these unique genes have no known function.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Of the remainder of the unique proteins that have an identified function, most belong to the Methanobacteriati and are involved in methanogenesis.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The proteins that archaea, bacteria and eukaryotes share form a common core of cell function, relating mostly to transcription, translation, and nucleotide metabolism.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Other characteristic archaeal features are the organization of genes of related function – such as enzymes that catalyze steps in the same metabolic pathway into novel operons, and large differences in tRNA genes and their aminoacyl tRNA synthetases.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Transcription in archaea more closely resembles eukaryotic than bacterial transcription, with the archaeal RNA polymerase being very close to its equivalent in eukaryotes, while archaeal translation shows signs of both bacterial and eukaryotic equivalents.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Post-transcriptional modification is simpler than in eukaryotes, since most archaeal genes lack introns, although there are many introns in their transfer RNA and ribosomal RNA genes, and introns may occur in a few protein-encoding genes.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] When the hyperthermophilic archaea *Sulfolobus solfataricus* and *Sulfolobus acidocaldarius* are exposed to DNA-damaging UV irradiation or to the agents bleomycin or mitomycin C, species-specific cellular aggregation is induced.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Aggregation in *S. solfataricus* could not be induced by other physical stressors, such as pH or temperature shift, suggesting that aggregation is induced specifically by DNA damage.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Ajon et al. showed that UV-induced cellular aggregation mediates chromosomal marker exchange with high frequency in *S. acidocaldarius*.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Recombination rates exceeded those of uninduced cultures by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Frols et al. and Ajon et al. hypothesized that cellular aggregation enhances species-specific DNA transfer between *Sulfolobus* cells in order to provide increased repair of damaged DNA by means of homologous recombination.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This response may be a primitive form of sexual interaction similar to the more well-studied bacterial transformation systems that are also associated with species-specific DNA transfer between cells leading to homologous recombinational repair of DNA damage.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea are the target of a number of viruses in a diverse virosphere distinct from bacterial and eukaryotic viruses.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] They have been organized into 15–18 DNA-based families so far, but multiple species remain un-isolated and await classification.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These families can be informally divided into two groups: archaea-specific and cosmopolitan.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaeal-specific viruses target only archaean species and currently include 12 families.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Numerous unique, previously unidentified viral structures have been observed in this group, including: bottle-shaped, spindle-shaped, coil-shaped, and droplet-shaped viruses.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] While the reproductive cycles and genomic mechanisms of archaea-specific species may be similar to other viruses, they bear unique characteristics that were specifically developed due to the morphology of host cells they infect.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Their virus release mechanisms differ from that of other phages.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Bacteriophages generally undergo either lytic pathways, lysogenic pathways, or (rarely) a mix of the two.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Most archaea-specific viral strains maintain a stable, somewhat lysogenic, relationship with their hosts – appearing as a chronic infection.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This involves the gradual, and continuous, production and release of virions without killing the host cell.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Prangishyili (2013) noted that it has been hypothesized that tailed archaeal phages originated from bacteriophages capable of infecting haloarchaeal species.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] If the hypothesis is correct, it can be concluded that other double-stranded DNA viruses that make up the rest of the archaea-specific group are their own unique group in the global viral community.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] (2018) states that the high levels of horizontal gene transfer, rapid mutation rates in viral genomes, and lack of universal gene sequences have led researchers to perceive the evolutionary pathway of archaeal viruses as a network.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The lack of similarities among phylogenetic markers in this network and the global virosphere, as well as external linkages to non-viral elements, may suggest that some species of archaea specific viruses evolved from non-viral mobile genetic elements (MGE).
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These viruses have been studied in most detail in thermophilics, particularly the orders Sulfolobales and Thermoproteales.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Two groups of single-stranded DNA viruses that infect archaea have been recently isolated.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] One group is exemplified by the *Halorubrum pleomorphic virus 1* (*Pleolipoviridae*) infecting halophilic archaea, and the other one by the *Aeropyrum coil-shaped virus* (*Spiraviridae*) infecting a hyperthermophilic (optimal growth at 90–95 °C) host.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Notably, the latter virus has the largest currently reported ssDNA genome.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Defenses against these viruses may involve RNA interference from repetitive DNA sequences that are related to the genes of the viruses.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea reproduce asexually by binary or multiple fission, fragmentation, or budding; mitosis and meiosis do not occur, so if a species of archaea exists in more than one form, all have the same genetic material.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Cell division is controlled in a cell cycle; after the cell's chromosome is replicated and the two daughter chromosomes separate, the cell divides.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In the genus *Sulfolobus*, the cycle has characteristics that are similar to both bacterial and eukaryotic systems.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] The chromosomes replicate from multiple starting points (origins of replication) using DNA polymerases that resemble the equivalent eukaryotic enzymes.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In Methanobacteriati the cell division protein FtsZ, which forms a contracting ring around the cell, and the components of the septum that is constructed across the center of the cell, are similar to their bacterial equivalents.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] In cren- and thaumarchaea, the cell division machinery Cdv fulfills a similar role.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] This machinery is related to the eukaryotic ESCRT-III machinery which, while best known for its role in cell sorting, also has been seen to fulfill a role in separation between divided cell, suggesting an ancestral role in cell division.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Both bacteria and eukaryotes, but not archaea, make spores.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Quorum sensing was originally thought to not exist in Archaea, but recent studies have shown evidence of some species being able to perform cross-talk through quorum sensing.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Other studies have shown syntrophic interactions between archaea and bacteria during biofilm growth.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Although research is limited in archaeal quorum sensing, some studies have uncovered LuxR proteins in archaeal species, displaying similarities with bacteria LuxR, and ultimately allowing for the detection of small molecules that are used in high density communication.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Similarly to bacteria, Archaea LuxR solos have shown to bind to AHLs (lactones) and non-AHLs ligans, which is a large part in performing intraspecies, interspecies, and interkingdom communication through quorum sensing.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Archaea are known to form biofilms, a common strategy among microorganisms.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Quorum sensing is thought to play a role in Archaeal biofilm formation, but less is known about Archaeal quorum sensing than Bacterial quorum sensing.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Some Archaea have been observed to form biofilms when the pH is a specific value, without necessarily relying on quorum sensing for instance.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] These biofilms are sessile communities of micro-organisms (they can contain multiple different species) that produce extracellular polymeric substances, which are used to create a matrix, within which the micro-organisms can grow.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Biofilms are beneficial as they: protect organisms from abiotic stresses; facilitate horizontal gene transfer; and enable syntropy to take place.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Biofilm formation has a number of stages: attachment; micro-colony formation; maturation; and dispersal.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] During the attachment phase the Archaea are reversibly attached to a surface by type-4 pili and archaella.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Some Archaea possess other structures involved in attachment such as hami; fimbriae; or cannulae.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] During the micro colony phase, the extracellular polymeric substance matrix is produced, and numerous archaea have been observed to produce pills and nanowires between cells.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] During the maturation phase the matrix takes on a sophisticated architecture, such as including pathways for waste to exit the biofilms.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Different archaea have been observed to produce biofilms with different architectures.
[src:archaea/archaea-p01] Finally, dispersal can take place, where cells begin to leave the biofilm, this process has been observed in Archaea but the mechanisms behind it are not understood.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Archaea exist in a broad range of habitats, are recognized as a major part of global ecosystems, and may represent about 20% of microbial cells in the oceans as well as a large number of cells in sea floor sediment.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] However, the first-discovered archaeans were extremophiles.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Indeed, some archaea survive high temperatures, often above 100 °C (212 °F), as found in geysers, black smokers, and oil wells.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Other common habitats include very cold habitats and highly saline, acidic, or alkaline water, but archaea include mesophiles that grow in mild conditions, in swamps and marshland, sewage, the oceans, the intestinal tract of animals, and soils.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Similar to PGPR, Archaea are considered a source of plant growth promotion as well.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Extremophile archaea are members of four main physiological groups.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] These are the halophiles, thermophiles, alkaliphiles, and acidophiles.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] These groups are not comprehensive or phylum-specific, nor are they mutually exclusive, since some archaea belong to several groups.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Nonetheless, they are a useful starting point for classification.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Halophiles, including the genus *Halobacterium*, live in extremely saline environments such as salt lakes and outnumber their bacterial counterparts at salinities greater than 20–25%.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Thermophiles grow best at temperatures above 45 °C (113 °F), in places such as hot springs; *hyperthermophilic* archaea grow optimally at temperatures greater than 80 °C (176 °F).
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] The archaeal *Methanopyrus kandleri* Strain 116 can even reproduce at 122 °C (252 °F), the highest recorded temperature of any organism.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Other archaea exist in very acidic or alkaline conditions.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] For example, one of the most extreme archaean acidophiles is *Picrophilus torridus*, which grows at pH 0, which is equivalent to thriving in 1.2 molar sulfuric acid.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] This resistance to extreme environments has made archaea the focus of speculation about the possible properties of extraterrestrial life.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Some extremophile habitats are not dissimilar to those on Mars, leading to the suggestion that viable microbes could be transferred between planets in meteorites.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Recently, several studies have shown that archaea exist not only in mesophilic and thermophilic environments but are also present, sometimes in high numbers, at low temperatures as well.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] For example, archaea are common in cold oceanic environments such as polar seas.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Even more significant are the large numbers of archaea found throughout the world's oceans in non-extreme habitats among the plankton community (as part of the picoplankton).
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Although these archaea can be present in extremely high numbers (up to 40% of the microbial biomass), almost none of these species have been isolated and studied in pure culture.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Consequently, our understanding of the role of archaea in ocean ecology is rudimentary, so their full influence on global biogeochemical cycles remains largely unexplored.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Some marine Thermoproteota are capable of nitrification, suggesting these organisms may affect the oceanic nitrogen cycle, although these oceanic Thermoproteota may also use other sources of energy.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Vast numbers of archaea are also found in the sediments that cover the sea floor, with these organisms making up at least 12.8%, and in many places, the majority of living cells at depths over 1 meter below the ocean bottom.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Archaea recycle elements such as carbon, nitrogen, and sulfur through their various habitats.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Archaea carry out many steps in the nitrogen cycle.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] This includes both reactions that remove nitrogen from ecosystems (such as nitrate-based respiration and denitrification) as well as processes that introduce nitrogen (such as nitrate assimilation and nitrogen fixation).
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Researchers recently discovered archaeal involvement in ammonia oxidation reactions.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] These reactions are particularly important in the oceans.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] The archaea also appear crucial for ammonia oxidation in soils.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] They produce nitrite, which other microbes then oxidize to nitrate.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Plants and other organisms consume the latter.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] In the carbon cycle, methanogen archaea remove hydrogen and play an important role in the decay of organic matter by the populations of microorganisms that act as decomposers in anaerobic ecosystems, such as sediments, marshes, and sewage-treatment works.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] The well-characterized interactions between archaea and other organisms are either mutual or commensal.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Mutualism is an interaction between individuals of different species that results in positive (beneficial) effects on per capita reproduction and/or survival of the interacting populations.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] One well-understood example of mutualism is the interaction between protozoa and methanogenic archaea in the digestive tracts of animals that digest cellulose, such as ruminants and termites.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] In these anaerobic environments, protozoa break down plant cellulose to obtain energy.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] This process releases hydrogen as a waste product, but high levels of hydrogen reduce energy production.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] When methanogens convert hydrogen to methane, protozoa benefit from more energy.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] In anaerobic protozoa, such as *Plagiopyla frontata*, *Trimyema*, *Heterometopus* and *Metopus contortus*, archaea reside inside the protozoa and consume hydrogen produced in their hydrogenosomes.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Archaea associate with larger organisms, too.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] For example, the marine archaean *Cenarchaeum symbiosum* is an endosymbiont of the sponge *Axinella mexicana*.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Some archaea are commensals, benefiting from an association without helping or harming the other organism.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] For example, the methanogen *Methanobrevibacter smithii* is by far the most common archaean in the human flora, making up about one in ten of the prokaryotes in the human gut.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] In termites and in humans, these methanogens may in fact be mutualists, interacting with other microbes in the gut to aid digestion.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Archaean communities associate with a range of other organisms, such as on the surface of corals, and in the region of soil that surrounds plant roots (the rhizosphere).
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Although Archaea do not have a historical reputation of being pathogens, Archaea are often found with similar genomes to more common pathogens like *E. coli,* showing metabolic links and evolutionary history with today's pathogens.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Archaea have been inconsistently detected in clinical studies because of the lack of categorization of Archaea into more specific species.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] The reduced genome of *Candidatus* Sukunaarchaeum mirabile suggests it is a specialized parasite highly dependant on its dinoflagellate host.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Extremophile archaea, particularly those resistant either to heat or to extremes of acidity and alkalinity, are a source of enzymes that function under these harsh conditions.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] For example, thermostable DNA polymerases, such as the Pfu DNA polymerase from *Pyrococcus furiosus*, revolutionized molecular biology by allowing the polymerase chain reaction to be used in research as a simple and rapid technique for cloning DNA.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] In industry, amylases, galactosidases and pullulanases in other species of *Pyrococcus* that function at over 100 °C (212 °F) allow food processing at high temperatures, such as the production of low lactose milk and whey.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Enzymes from these thermophilic archaea also tend to be very stable in organic solvents, allowing their use in environmentally friendly processes in green chemistry that synthesize organic compounds.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] This stability makes them easier to use in structural biology.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Consequently, the counterparts of bacterial or eukaryotic enzymes from extremophile archaea are often used in structural studies.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] In contrast with the range of applications of archaean enzymes, the use of the organisms themselves in biotechnology is less developed.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Methanogenic archaea are a vital part of sewage treatment, since they are part of the community of microorganisms that carry out anaerobic digestion and produce biogas.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] In mineral processing, acidophilic archaea display promise for the extraction of metals from ores, including gold, cobalt and copper.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] Archaea host a new class of potentially useful antibiotics.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] A few of these archaeocins have been characterized, but hundreds more are believed to exist, especially within Halobacteria and *Sulfolobus*.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] These compounds differ in structure from bacterial antibiotics, so they may have novel modes of action.
[src:archaea/archaea-p02] In addition, they may allow the creation of new selectable markers for use in archaeal molecular biology.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] ATP synthase lies across a cellular membrane and forms an aperture that protons can cross from areas of high concentration to areas of low concentration, imparting energy for the synthesis of ATP.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] This electrochemical gradient is generated by the electron transport chain and allows cells to store energy in ATP for later use.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] In prokaryotic cells ATP synthase lies across the plasma membrane, while in eukaryotic cells it lies across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Organisms capable of photosynthesis also have ATP synthase across the thylakoid membrane, which in plants is located in the chloroplast and in cyanobacteria is located in the cytoplasm.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] ATP synthase is present in all organisms studied.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Eukaryotic ATP synthases are F-ATPases (which usually work as ATP synthases instead of ATPases in cellular environments) and running "in reverse" for an ATPase (ATPases catalyze the decomposition of ATP into ADP and a free phosphate ion).
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] This article deals mainly with this type.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] An F-ATPase consists of two main subunits, FO and F1, which has a rotational motor mechanism allowing for ATP production.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The F1 fraction derives its name from the term "Fraction 1" and FO (written as a subscript letter "o", not "zero") derives its name from being the binding fraction for oligomycin, a type of naturally derived antibiotic that is able to inhibit the FO unit of ATP synthase.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] These functional regions consist of different protein subunits — refer to tables.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] This enzyme is used in synthesis of ATP through aerobic respiration.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Located within the thylakoid membrane and the inner mitochondrial membrane, ATP synthase consists of two regions FO and F1.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] FO causes rotation of F1 and is made of c-ring and subunits a, two b, F6.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] F1 has a water-soluble part that can hydrolyze ATP.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] FO on the other hand has mainly hydrophobic regions.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] FO F1 creates a pathway for protons movement across the membrane.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The F1 portion of ATP synthase is hydrophilic and responsible for hydrolyzing ATP.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The F1 unit protrudes into the cytoplasm (matrix and stroma in mitochondria and chloroplasts respectively).
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Subunits α and β make a hexamer with 6 binding sites.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Three of them are catalytically inactive and they bind ADP.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Three other subunits catalyze the ATP synthesis.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The other F1 subunits γ, δ, and ε are a part of a rotational motor mechanism (rotor/axle).
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The γ subunit allows β to go through conformational changes (i.e., closed, half open, and open states) that allow for ATP to be bound and released once synthesized.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The F1 particle is large and can be seen in the transmission electron microscope by negative staining.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] These are particles of 9 nm diameter that pepper the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] FO is a water insoluble protein with eight subunits and a transmembrane ring.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The FO region of ATP synthase is a proton pore that is embedded in the mitochondrial membrane.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] It consists of three main subunits, a, b, and c.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Six c subunits make up the rotor ring, and subunit b makes up a stalk connecting to F1 OSCP that prevents the αβ hexamer from rotating.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Humans have six additional subunits, d, e, f, g, F6, and 8 (or A6L).
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] This part of the enzyme is located in the mitochondrial inner membrane and couples proton translocation to the rotation that causes ATP synthesis in the F1 region.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] In eukaryotes, mitochondrial FO forms membrane-bending dimers.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] These dimers self-arrange into long rows at the end of the cristae, possibly the first step of cristae formation.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] An atomic model for the dimeric yeast FO region was determined by cryo-EM at an overall resolution of 3.6 Å.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] In the 1960s through the 1970s, Paul Boyer, a UCLA Professor, developed the binding change, or flip-flop, mechanism theory, which postulated that ATP synthesis is dependent on a conformational change in ATP synthase generated by rotation of the gamma subunit.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Walker, then at the MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology in Cambridge, crystallized the F1 catalytic-domain of ATP synthase.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The structure, at the time the largest asymmetric protein structure known, indicated that Boyer's rotary-catalysis model was, in essence, correct.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] For elucidating this, Boyer and Walker shared half of the 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The crystal structure of the F1 showed alternating alpha and beta subunits (3 of each), arranged like segments of an orange around a rotating asymmetrical gamma subunit.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] A portion of the FO (the ring of c-subunits) rotates as the protons pass through the membrane.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The c-ring is tightly attached to the asymmetric central stalk (consisting primarily of the gamma subunit), causing it to rotate within the alpha3beta3 of F1 causing the 3 catalytic nucleotide binding sites to go through a series of conformational changes that lead to ATP synthesis.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The major F1 subunits are prevented from rotating in sympathy with the central stalk rotor by a peripheral stalk that joins the alpha3beta3 to the non-rotating portion of FO.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The structure of the intact ATP synthase is currently known at low-resolution from electron cryo-microscopy (cryo-EM) studies of the complex.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The cryo-EM model of ATP synthase suggests that the peripheral stalk is a flexible structure that wraps around the complex as it joins F1 to FO.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Under the right conditions, the enzyme reaction can also be carried out in reverse, with ATP hydrolysis driving proton pumping across the membrane.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The binding change mechanism involves the active site of a β subunit's cycling between three states.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] In the "loose" state, ADP and phosphate enter the active site; in the adjacent diagram, this is shown in pink.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The enzyme then undergoes a change in shape and forces these molecules together, with the active site in the resulting "tight" state (shown in red) binding the newly produced ATP molecule with very high affinity.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Finally, the active site cycles back to the open state (orange), releasing ATP and binding more ADP and phosphate, ready for the next cycle of ATP production.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Like other enzymes, the activity of F1FO ATP synthase is reversible.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Large-enough quantities of ATP cause it to create a transmembrane proton gradient, this is used by fermenting bacteria that do not have an electron transport chain, but rather hydrolyze ATP to make a proton gradient, which they use to drive flagella and the transport of nutrients into the cell.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] In respiring bacteria under physiological conditions, ATP synthase, in general, runs in the opposite direction, creating ATP while using the proton motive force created by the electron transport chain as a source of energy.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The overall process of creating energy in this fashion is termed oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The same process takes place in the mitochondria, where ATP synthase is located in the inner mitochondrial membrane and the F1-part projects into the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] By pumping proton cations into the matrix, the ATP-synthase converts ADP into ATP.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The evolution of ATP synthase is thought to have been modular whereby two functionally independent subunits became associated and gained new functionality.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] This association appears to have occurred early in evolutionary history, because essentially the same structure and activity of ATP synthase enzymes are present in all kingdoms of life.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The F-ATP synthase displays high functional and mechanistic similarity to the V-ATPase.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] However, whereas the F-ATP synthase generates ATP by utilising a proton gradient, the V-ATPase generates a proton gradient at the expense of ATP, generating pH values of as low as 1.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The F1 region also shows significant similarity to hexameric DNA helicases (especially the Rho factor), and the entire enzyme region shows some similarity to H+ -powered T3SS or flagellar motor complexes.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The α3β3 hexamer of the F1 region shows significant structural similarity to hexameric DNA helicases; both form a ring with 3-fold rotational symmetry with a central pore.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The H+ motor of the FO particle shows great functional similarity to the H+ motors that drive flagella.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Both feature a ring of many small alpha-helical proteins that rotate relative to nearby stationary proteins, using a H+ potential gradient as an energy source.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] This link is tenuous, however, as the overall structure of flagellar motors is far more complex than that of the FO particle and the ring with about 30 rotating proteins is far larger than the 10, 11, or 14 helical proteins in the FO complex.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] More recent structural data do however show that the ring and the stalk are structurally similar to the F1 particle.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The modular evolution theory for the origin of ATP synthase suggests that two subunits with independent function, a DNA helicase with ATPase activity and a H+ motor, were able to bind, and the rotation of the motor drove the ATPase activity of the helicase in reverse.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] This complex then evolved greater efficiency and eventually developed into today's intricate ATP synthases.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Alternatively, the DNA helicase/H+ motor complex may have had H+ pump activity with the ATPase activity of the helicase driving the H+ motor in reverse.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] This may have evolved to carry out the reverse reaction and act as an ATP synthase.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] A variety of natural and synthetic inhibitors of ATP synthase have been discovered.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] These have been used to probe the structure and mechanism of ATP synthase.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] There are several classes of ATP synthase inhibitors, including peptide inhibitors, polyphenolic phytochemicals, polyketides, organotin compounds, polyenic α-pyrone derivatives, cationic inhibitors, substrate analogs, amino acid modifiers, and other miscellaneous chemicals.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Some of the most commonly used ATP synthase inhibitors are oligomycin and DCCD.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Bacterial F-ATPases can occasionally operate in reverse, turning them into an ATPase.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Some bacteria have no F-ATPase, using an A/V-type ATPase bidirectionally.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Yeast ATP synthase is one of the best-studied eukaryotic ATP synthases; and five F1, eight FO subunits, and seven associated proteins have been identified.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Most of these proteins have homologues in other eukaryotes.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] In plants, ATP synthase is also present in chloroplasts (CF1FO-ATP synthase).
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The enzyme is integrated into thylakoid membrane; the CF1-part sticks into stroma, where dark reactions of photosynthesis (also called the light-independent reactions or the Calvin cycle) and ATP synthesis take place.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The overall structure and the catalytic mechanism of the chloroplast ATP synthase are almost the same as those of the bacterial enzyme.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] However, in chloroplasts, the proton motive force is generated not by respiratory electron transport chain but by primary photosynthetic proteins.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The synthase has a 40-aa insert in the gamma-subunit to inhibit wasteful activity when dark.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The ATP synthase isolated from bovine (*Bos taurus*) heart mitochondria is, in terms of biochemistry and structure, the best-characterized ATP synthase.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Beef heart is used as a source for the enzyme because of the high concentration of mitochondria in cardiac muscle.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Their genes have close homology to human ATP synthases.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Eukaryotes belonging to some divergent lineages have very special organizations of the ATP synthase.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] A euglenozoa ATP synthase forms a dimer with a boomerang-shaped F1 head like other mitochondrial ATP synthases, but the FO subcomplex has many unique subunits.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] The inhibitory IF1 also binds differently, in a way shared with trypanosomatida.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Apicomplexans, such as *Plasmodium*, utilise a hexameric ATP synthase organisation existing as a trimer of ATP synthase dimers.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] These hexameric assemblies arrange into pentagonal pyramids, which induce a unique bulbous cristae membrane morphology.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] This organisation is underpinned by both apicomplexan-specific subunits and cardiolipins.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Archaea do not generally have an F-ATPase.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Instead, they synthesize ATP using the A-ATPase/synthase, a rotary machine structurally similar to the V-ATPase but mainly functioning as an ATP synthase.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] Like the bacteria F-ATPase, it is believed to also function as an ATPase.
[src:archaea/atp-synthase] F-ATPase gene linkage and gene order are widely conserved across ancient prokaryote lineages, implying that this system already existed at a date before the last universal common ancestor, the LUCA.
